We may have a few minor philosophical differences now and then, but in this we always have and will continue to strongly agree, *Judge no one!*<br><br>
One of the most prevalent degrading, dishonoring, denegrating, and discriminatory treatments given to many Vietnam Veterans has been to judge them to standards that are clearly inappropriate. After the wild eyed protestors<br>
who did their &quot;baby killer&quot; and spitting thing, and the discrimination at restaurants, public places, and in the workforce, it was veterans of WW2 and the Korean Conflict who were very arrogantly vocal in their condemnation of Vietnam Veterans. I seem to recall that the VFW or the American Legion were NOT the places that welcomed the 'NamVet as a fellow warrior. I stayed away for that reason. Why join where you were unwelcome.<br><br>
It is funny, but my father was a WW2 and Korean Conflict Veteran, and he did not think like &quot;Lewis&quot; at all. Isn't that funny. Maybe the problem lies with individuals, and is not systemic.<br><br>
I wonder how &quot;Lewis&quot; would feel if we returned the same treatment. I suspect he would whine all the way to wherever he hangs out, and be &quot;so&quot; hurt. Boo Hoo!<br><br>
